## Client Portal Rules

- Every portal operation enforces: client can only see their own properties, only approved/published outputs are returned, draft and consultant-only data is excluded.
- PII masking applied per tenant policy on all portal responses.
- Clients must never see consultant-only working notes, draft hypotheses, or unrestricted underlying PII (spec_1 §11.2, line 1064).
- "Limited explore" provides only pre-approved filters and comparisons — no raw SQL, no unrestricted pivots.
- The portal reads from the same data stores as the consultant workspace but applies a strict approval filter.

## Trend & Trajectory Rules

- Trend marts in ClickHouse are materialized per-property after each assessment completes.
- 5 trend-ready fact tables (ORDER BY from DDL):
  - `fact_assessment_score` — score per area per assessment, ORDER BY `(property_id, assessment_date)` (DDL line 2741)
  - `fact_assessment_finding` — finding persistence per domain per assessment, ORDER BY `(property_id, assessment_date)` (DDL line 2760)
  - `fact_recommendation_status` — recommendation status changes, ORDER BY `(property_id, status_date)` (DDL line 2778)
  - `fact_property_kpi_period` — period-level KPIs, ORDER BY `(property_id, period_start, kpi_name)` (DDL line 2795)
  - `fact_unit_chronicity` — chronic vacancy/issue/turnover per unit, ORDER BY `(property_id, unit_id)` (DDL line 2813). Column is `chronic_type` (not `chronicity_type`).
- Recurring finding detection: a finding is "recurring" if the same domain + finding_type appears in 2+ assessments for the same property.
- Chronic unit detection: a unit is "chronic" based on configurable thresholds (e.g., vacant > 90 days, 3+ turnovers in 12 months).
- Assessment comparison requires both assessments to be for the same property. Cross-property comparison is not supported.

## Recommendation Tracking Rules

- Recommendations are structured objects with: domain, target_entity_type, target_entity_id, priority (critical/high/medium/low), title, description, expected_impact, owner, due_date, status (open/in_progress/completed/deferred/rejected), verification_evidence (spec_1 §14.3, lines 1192-1201).
- Status transitions must be validated: not all transitions are allowed (e.g., cannot go from `completed` back to `open`).
- Each status update stores verification evidence (what changed, who verified, evidence links).
- The next assessment evaluates both operational performance and execution discipline (whether recommendations were followed).

## Testing Rules

- Client portal: test that client users cannot see consultant-only data, draft outputs, or other clients' data.
- Client portal: test each module returns only approved content.
- Trend marts: test materialization produces correct row counts per assessment.
- Recurring findings: test detection with 1 assessment (no recurrence), 2 assessments (same finding = recurring), 2 assessments (different findings = not recurring).
- Recommendation tracking: test all valid status transitions and verify invalid transitions are rejected.
- Assessment comparison: test that comparing assessments for different properties returns `DifferentProperties` error.
- Chronic unit detection: test with units above and below chronicity thresholds.
- All tests use **pytest**. Shared fixtures in `tests/conftest.py`.

## What NOT To Build In This Phase

- Do not implement the door opener assessment type — that's Phase 6.
- Do not implement the extension SDK — that's Phase 6.
- Do not modify the scoring engine or diagnostic pipeline — those are Phase 3 deliverables. This phase consumes their outputs.
